THE RISK:
{
 "id": "enterprise-gpu-busbar-half-refuted",
 "title": "The 'refuted' GPU-pod doubt was only half-refuted: dense enterprise AI refresh ships on DC busbar, hollowing seg.enterprise from both ends",
 "narrative": "Refinement cycle 1 closed the 'GPU pods skip PDUs' doubt because NVIDIA reference architectures ship PDU variants. But the vendor publishes parallel architectures: the AC/PDU version is the fallback, while the flagship dense design routes power via DC busbar with materially lower PDU attach per rack. The only part of enterprise on-premise that is growing is exactly this GPU-pod build-out; the legacy base is bleeding ~2pp of capacity share per year toward 19% by 2031. So the 0.29 enterprise slice is squeezed twice — the shrinking legacy half keeps buying PDUs it already owns, and the growing AI half is steered toward the substitute. A checkbox marked 'confirmed' is carrying 29% of the TAM.",
 "category": "boundary",
 "targetNodes": [
  "seg.enterprise"
 ],
 "mechanism": [
  {
   "step": "trigger",
   "text": "Enterprise on-premise capacity growth is now driven almost entirely by GenAI/GPU infrastructure after a sustained no-growth period, and the flagship reference architecture for the densest pods uses DC busbar with sharply reduced rack-PDU attach, with the AC/PDU variant positioned as legacy fallback",
   "refs": [
    "digest:seg-mix#c19",
    "ledger:seg.enterprise"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "propagation",
   "text": "The growing sub-segment of enterprise carries falling PDU content per rack while the legacy on-prem base shrinks ~2pp/year (from 32% end-2025 toward 19% by 2031) — effective enterprise rack-PDU demand falls on both the growth side and the base side simultaneously",
   "refs": [
    "digest:seg-mix#c5",
    "digest:seg-mix#c4"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "model-impact",
   "text": "seg.enterprise 0.29 (crossCheck marked 'value confirmed') overstates the PDU-addressable enterprise slice; during the venture's 12-month window the realistic value sits below the model's own 0.24 low band, and the funnel's second-largest segment quietly deflates",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:seg.enterprise",
    "digest:seg-mix#c2"
   ]
  }
 ],
 "whyMissable": "The doubt was explicitly investigated and stamped 'refuted' in refinement cycle 1 — the risk register shows a closed item. The binary confirmed/refuted framing hides that PDU-shipping and PDU-attach-per-MW are different questions: NVIDIA shipping PDU variants does not mean the dense builds that constitute all the segment's growth actually use them.",
 "expectedObviousness": "medium",
 "falsifier": "Attach-rate evidence from 2026 CE enterprise GPU-pod deployments (integrator BOMs or vendor order data) showing rack-PDU counts per rack at or above the legacy ≥3-per-rack norm in the majority of dense installs.",
 "likelihood": {
  "value": 0.33,
  "rationale": "The parallel-architecture steering is documented in vendor reference designs and the enterprise share decline (2pp/year) is a multi-vintage Synergy trend; uncertainty is whether CE enterprises actually deploy the flagship density tier within 12 months or stay on air-cooled AC/PDU designs [evidence revision: The base-rate half of the mechanism (2pp/year decline, GPU-driven growth) is strongly confirmed, but the load-bearing 'sharply reduced rack-PDU attach' premise is undercut by NVIDIA's own AC-power SuperPOD reference architecture showing a very high rPDU count (432+96) — the busbar reduces PDUs on compute racks but the surrounding network/storage/management racks in a pod still carry standard AC PDUs. The falsifier is at least partially met at the pod level. This lowers the probability that seg.enterprise falls below its 0.24 low band within 12 months, so I trim from 0.40 to 0.33.]",
  "basis": "evidence",
  "revisedFrom": 0.4
 },
 "perturbation": [
  {
   "nodeId": "seg.enterprise",
   "op": "set",
   "value": 0.2,
   "note": "GPU-driven growth adopts busbar attach while legacy base decays; effective PDU-addressable enterprise share drops below the model's 0.24 low band"
  }
 ],
 "indicators": [
  {
   "signal": "Which power variant (AC/PDU vs DC busbar) is default in NVIDIA/OEM pod reference-architecture documentation revisions",
   "where": "NVIDIA GTC reference-architecture sessions and DGX/MGX pod deployment guides; Dell/HPE AI-factory configurators",
   "threshold": "DC busbar becomes the documented default for ≥50% of published dense-pod configurations",
   "updates": "increases"
  },
  {
   "signal": "Enterprise/IT-segment rack-PDU revenue commentary from incumbents",
   "where": "Vertiv and Schneider quarterly earnings calls, rack-power and IT-channel product-line commentary",
   "threshold": "Enterprise PDU line flat or declining while integrated-rack/busbar lines grow double-digit for two consecutive quarters",
   "updates": "increases"
  }
 ],
 "mitigations": [
  {
   "action": "Commission an attach-rate teardown of CE enterprise GPU-pod installs (PDUs per rack by density tier) via 5–8 integrator interviews",
   "type": "information",
   "voiNodeId": "seg.enterprise",
   "note": "Directly re-bases the enterprise slice on measured attach rather than a binary confirmed/refuted flag"
  },
  {
   "action": "Position the Year-1 product for the air-cooled enterprise refresh tier (where AC/PDU remains default) and roadmap a high-amp/DC-compatible SKU for dense pods",
   "type": "strategic",
   "voiNodeId": null,
   "note": "Decouples Year-1 revenue from the sub-segment where substitution bites first"
  }
 ],
 "evidenceStatus": "contested",
 "evidence": [
  {
   "title": "Major Components — NVIDIA SuperPOD with DGX B300 Systems and AC Power Reference Architecture",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "NVIDIA",
   "date": "2025-10-30",
   "excerpt": "432 DGX rPDU for Standard Rack Raritan (PX3-5091R-P1Q2R1A5) or Equiv; 96 Mgmt Vertical PDU Raritan (PX3-5747V-V2) or equivalent — NVIDIA publishes an AC Power Reference Architecture with heavy per-rack PDU content as a first-class variant.",
   "url": "https://docs.nvidia.com/dgx-superpod/reference-architecture/scalable-infrastructure-b300-xdr/latest/components.html",
   "attached": true
  },
  {
   "title": "Hyperscale Operators to Account for 67% of all Data Center Capacity by 2031",
   "sourceType": "analyst-estimate",
   "publisher": "Synergy Research Group",
   "date": "2026",
   "excerpt": "on-premise data centers with just 32% of the total... Looking ahead to 2031, on-premise will drop to just 19%... on-premise data center capacity is receiving something of a boost thanks to GenAI applications and GPU infrastructure... on-premise share of the total will drop by around two percentage points per year.",
   "url": "https://www.srgresearch.com/articles/hyperscale-operators-to-account-for-67-of-all-data-center-capacity-by-2031",
   "attached": true
  },
  {
   "title": "Hardware — NVIDIA DGX GB Rack Scale Systems User Guide",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "NVIDIA",
   "date": null,
   "excerpt": "The complete DGX GB rack system comprises compute trays... power shelves, a bus bar, and liquid cooling manifolds — confirming the flagship dense design routes power via DC busbar.",
   "url": "https://docs.nvidia.com/dgx/dgxgb200-user-guide/hardware.html",
   "attached": true
  }
 ],
 "stances": [
  {
   "url": "https://docs.nvidia.com/dgx/dgxgb200-user-guide/hardware.html",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "The complete DGX GB rack system comprises compute trays with one or two compute boards, NVLink switch trays, an NVLink passive copper cable backplane, power shelves, a bus bar, and liquid cooling manifolds."
  },
  {
   "url": "https://docs.nvidia.com/dgx-superpod/reference-architecture/scalable-infrastructure-b300-xdr/latest/components.html",
   "stance": "contradicts",
   "quote": "432 DGX rPDU for Standard Rack Raritan (PX3-5091R-P1Q2R1A5) or Equiv\n96 Mgmt Vertical PDU Raritan (PX3-5747V-V2) or equivalent"
  },
  {
   "url": "https://www.srgresearch.com/articles/hyperscale-operators-to-account-for-67-of-all-data-center-capacity-by-2031",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "After a sustained period of essentially no growth, on-premise data center capacity is receiving something of a boost thanks to GenAI applications and GPU infrastructure. Nonetheless, on-premise share of the total will drop by around two percentage points per year"
  },
  {
   "url": "https://www.crn.com/news/data-center/2026/data-center-market-share-face-off-hyperscalers-vs-colocation-vs-enterprise",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "By the end of 2025, that market dropped to 32 percent share and is expected to fall to just 19 percent by 2031."
  }
 ]
}

